rocesses?\n3. Why is it important for all participants in a group to communicate their dissent from decisions they do not agree with, in order to allow for alternative ideas to be considered?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "3aeef05b-db6e-4069-ad22-f370d931f06e", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "17", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "3991f8b51e0e166f8c70c085df4bb046e8e1a2449dfdff1522dcd4459b31a767", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "cfb05f31-ca39-4eb1-b2ea-54041bca4098", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "17", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "11aebede9386466a5586c8d9a2966230fc52695942c44a5ea3a6cb43dbb21cbe", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "528b407f-999c-4105-a32b-23941b0c7788", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "479edebba50ef4f162a6ca6b2d1fcbc6a0b50c448194c0a3ea622cd88e411d54", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "in response to the question or proposal from the Chair:\nThumb Up = complete support and good feeling, no doubts, questions, or concerns\nPalm up= strong support\nOn the Fence (hand straight out as if about to shake someone\u2019s hand) = undecided due to \nhaving questions, doubts, or alternative ideas. \nPalm down= A lot of doubts\nThumb Down = complete doubt or negative feeling, with many questions/concerns\nFist = major concern about the nature/timing/language of a proposal or question to the \ndegree that the current process must be interrupted and an alternative introduced.  \nThe Chair surveys the signs of the group and asks those with thumbs down to describe why \nthey feel the way they do and to articulate an alternative or at least to identify the specific \nparts of the proposal they find most problematic (followed by \u201cpalm down\u201d, \u201con the fence\u201d, \n\u201cpalm up\u201d). \nIt is crucial that everyone participating in consensus is encouraged to communicate dissent \nfrom decisions that they do not agree with so that alternative ideas are given space for \nconsideration. And it", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 945, "end_char_idx": 2017, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "528b407f-999c-4105-a32b-23941b0c7788": {"__data__": {"id_": "528b407f-999c-4105-a32b-23941b0c7788", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "17", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include a system for indicating support or dissent during discussions or decision-making processes within a group, such as using hand gestures like thumbs up, palm up, on the fence, palm down, thumb down, and fist. The section emphasizes the importance of encouraging all participants to communicate their dissent from decisions they do not agree with, in order to allow for alternative ideas to be considered. The Chair plays a role in facilitating this process by surveying the signs of the group and addressing concerns raised by those with dissenting opinions.", "next_section_summary": "The section discusses the process of consensus decision-making within a group. It explains that after discussing dissenting feelings and alternatives, the Chair may facilitate more discussion or rephrase the proposal until everyone in the group has a similar feeling. When everyone indicates agreement with a proposal through hand signs, the Chair can make a formal proposal for consensus. If everyone in the group shows a Thumb Up or Palms Up sign, 100% consensus is achieved. If consensus is not reached after multiple rounds of discussion, the Chair may suggest revisiting the issue at another time.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the process of consensus decision-making within a group, where the Chair surveys the group for signs of agreement or disagreement with a proposal. Those with dissenting opinions are encouraged to articulate their concerns and propose alternatives. It emphasizes the importance of allowing space for alternative ideas and for those blocking decisions to propose alternatives.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does the Chair facilitate the consensus decision-making process within a group, particularly when there are dissenting opinions?\n2. What are the specific hand gestures used in indicating support or dissent during discussions or decision-making processes within a group, as outlined in the document?\n3. What steps are taken if consensus is not reached after multiple rounds of discussion within a group, according to the guidelines provided in the document?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "3aeef05b-db6e-4069-ad22-f370d931f06e", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "17", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "3991f8b51e0e166f8c70c085df4bb046e8e1a2449dfdff1522dcd4459b31a767", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "10540ccb-b777-4557-a19b-046446c1d57a", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "17", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "3219832667a41c3e2e40d2c870a639e3cf46bcef41d26a5b09932204aa17c590", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "of a proposal or question to the \ndegree that the current process must be interrupted and an alternative introduced.  \nThe Chair surveys the signs of the group and asks those with thumbs down to describe why \nthey feel the way they do and to articulate an alternative or at least to identify the specific \nparts of the proposal they find most problematic (followed by \u201cpalm down\u201d, \u201con the fence\u201d, \n\u201cpalm up\u201d). \nIt is crucial that everyone participating in consensus is encouraged to communicate dissent \nfrom decisions that they do not agree with so that alternative ideas are given space for \nconsideration. And it is crucial that those blocking decisions propose alternatives.\nCONSENSUS \nDECISION-MAKING\n1.\n2.\n3.\n4.\n\u2022\n\u2022\n\u2022\n\u2022\n\u2022\n\u2022", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1402, "end_char_idx": 2131, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7669da6e-1c6a-4309-b504-d7873e65a039": {"__data__": {"id_": "7669da6e-1c6a-4309-b504-d7873e65a039", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "18", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the process of consensus decision-making within a group, where the Chair surveys the group for signs of agreement or disagreement with a proposal. Those with dissenting opinions are encouraged to articulate their concerns and propose alternatives. It emphasizes the importance of allowing space for alternative ideas and for those blocking decisions to propose alternatives.", "next_section_summary": "The section discusses the concept of conflict of interest, which occurs when someone in a position of trust has competing professional or personal interests that may interfere with their ability to remain impartial. It provides sample by-laws related to conflicts of interest, including guidelines for excusing oneself from decisions where a conflict exists and restrictions on board remuneration. The key topics covered include defining conflict of interest, guidelines for handling conflicts within an organization, and rules regarding board remuneration. The entities mentioned are individuals in positions of trust, organizations, and board members.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the process of consensus decision-making within a group. It explains that after discussing dissenting feelings and alternatives, the Chair may facilitate more discussion or rephrase the proposal until everyone in the group has a similar feeling. When everyone indicates agreement with a proposal through hand signs, the Chair can make a formal proposal for consensus. If everyone in the group shows a Thumb Up or Palms Up sign, 100% consensus is achieved. If consensus is not reached after multiple rounds of discussion, the Chair may suggest revisiting the issue at another time.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does the Chair of a group facilitate consensus decision-making by surveying the group for signs of agreement or disagreement with a proposal?\n2. What are the key indicators that 100% consensus has been achieved within a group using hand signs such as Thumb Up or Palms Up?\n3. In what situations does the Chair suggest revisiting an issue at another time if consensus is not reached after multiple rounds of discussion within a group?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "efd09f14-ac9e-4e54-9b95-a6ce81debebc", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "18", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "2594e7b047933a3f7d4ef39c495dafca13e31abd0f4e740b56637cfb806b575b", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "18\nCONSENSUS DECISION-MAKING\nAfter this sampling of dissenting feelings and voicing of alternatives the Chair may choose to \nfacilitate more discussion or rephrase the proposal or question again: \u201cHow do we all feel?\u201d\nWhen hand signs indicate that everyone in the group has a similar feeling about a proposal \nthe Chair then makes a formal proposal for consensus and if everyone in the group indicates a \nThumb Up or Palms Up then 100% consensus has been achieved. 100% CONSENSUS HAS NOT \nBEEN ACHIEVED UNLESS EVERYONE IN THE GROUP HAS THEIR PALM UP!!\nIf rounds of proposals and discussion stretch on for too long on one issue without reaching \nconsensus, the Chair proposes that the issue be revisited at another time. \n5.\n6.\n7.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 729, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "acd3d07a-cc70-491a-bad1-e6d517904c5a": {"__data__": {"id_": "acd3d07a-cc70-491a-bad1-e6d517904c5a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the process of consensus decision-making within a group. It explains that after discussing dissenting feelings and alternatives, the Chair may facilitate more discussion or rephrase the proposal until everyone in the group has a similar feeling. When everyone indicates agreement with a proposal through hand signs, the Chair can make a formal proposal for consensus. If everyone in the group shows a Thumb Up or Palms Up sign, 100% consensus is achieved. If consensus is not reached after multiple rounds of discussion, the Chair may suggest revisiting the issue at another time.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include conflict of interest among board members, specifically in relation to financial interests and remuneration. It outlines the obligation for board members to excuse themselves from discussions and voting on matters where they have a personal interest, and the prohibition on directors receiving profit from their position. The section also mentions the possibility of directors being paid for other services to the organization, with approval from the Board and the director abstaining from the decision. The section references relevant articles of the Quebec Provincial Civil Code regarding board members entering into contracts with the organization.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the concept of conflict of interest, which occurs when someone in a position of trust has competing professional or personal interests that may interfere with their ability to remain impartial. It provides sample by-laws related to conflicts of interest, including guidelines for excusing oneself from decisions where a conflict exists and restrictions on board remuneration. The key topics covered include defining conflict of interest, guidelines for handling conflicts within an organization, and rules regarding board remuneration. The entities mentioned are individuals in positions of trust, organizations, and board members.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does the document outline the process of handling conflicts of interest within a board of directors, specifically in relation to financial interests and remuneration?\n2. What are the key guidelines and by-laws provided in the document for individuals in positions of trust to handle conflicts of interest and ensure impartiality in decision-making?\n3. How does the document address the issue of board members receiving profit from their position, and what steps are outlined to ensure transparency and ethical conduct within the organization?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "f087677d-dc40-4313-97b1-9556bc2a631b", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "53e0d4f2fd97b3c71f927d8583b386062ba8900e88e6855a4dd87aa0c4fea3bd", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "3c24b291-c5b7-4609-911b-a322b4689baa", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "a8a620b0425419296e7699c98b5fb4c5c0d8a198dd9728c5cb8e281525be6c8f", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "19\nCONFLICT OF INTEREST\nWhat is a \u201cconflict of interest\u201d?\nA conflict of interest occurs when someone in a position of trust has competing professional or \npersonal interests. Such competing interests have the potential to interfere with the person\u2019s ability \nto remain impartial as they fulfill their duties. A conflict of interest exists even if no unethical or \ninappropriate actions are taken.\nSample \u201cconflict of interest\u201d by-laws:\nGeneral Conflict of Interest:  Anyone participating in a decision on behalf of the organization and \nwho has or is perceived to have a financial, personal, or official interest in that decision of such \nnature that it may prevent him/her from acting in an impartial manner is obliged to excuse him/\nherself from the discussion and voting on said item. In the case of the Board, such instances are to \nbe recorded in the meeting minutes.  \nConflict of Interest Relating to Board Remuneration: The directors shall serve without remuneration, \nand no director shall directly or indirectly receive any profit from his position as such, provided that \na director may be paid reasonable expenses", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 1125, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3c24b291-c5b7-4609-911b-a322b4689baa": {"__data__": {"id_": "3c24b291-c5b7-4609-911b-a322b4689baa", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the concept of conflict of interest, which occurs when someone in a position of trust has competing professional or personal interests that may interfere with their ability to remain impartial. It provides sample by-laws related to conflicts of interest, including guidelines for excusing oneself from decisions where a conflict exists and restrictions on board remuneration. The key topics covered include defining conflict of interest, guidelines for handling conflicts within an organization, and rules regarding board remuneration. The entities mentioned are individuals in positions of trust, organizations, and board members.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of the section include the prohibition of directors from receiving profits from their position, the allowance for directors to be reimbursed for expenses incurred in the performance of their duties, and the conditions under which directors may be paid for other services to the charity. The section also discusses the legal requirements for board members entering into contracts with the organization, including disclosure, recording in meeting minutes, and approval by the board with the abstention of the board member in question. Additionally, the section outlines the differing perspectives of Quebec Provincial Civil Code and Federal Common Law regarding board members receiving paid contracts from nonprofit organizations, with a mention of Revenue Canada's auditing requirements.", "section_summary": "The key topics of this section include conflict of interest among board members, specifically in relation to financial interests and remuneration. It outlines the obligation for board members to excuse themselves from discussions and voting on matters where they have a personal interest, and the prohibition on directors receiving profit from their position. The section also mentions the possibility of directors being paid for other services to the organization, with approval from the Board and the director abstaining from the decision. The section references relevant articles of the Quebec Provincial Civil Code regarding board members entering into contracts with the organization.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does the concept of conflict of interest apply to board members in nonprofit organizations, specifically in relation to financial interests and remuneration?\n2. What are the legal requirements for board members entering into contracts with the organization, including disclosure, recording in meeting minutes, and approval by the board with the abstention of the board member in question?\n3. What are the key differences between the perspectives of Quebec Provincial Civil Code and Federal Common Law regarding board members receiving paid contracts from nonprofit organizations, and what are Revenue Canada's auditing requirements in this regard?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "f087677d-dc40-4313-97b1-9556bc2a631b", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "53e0d4f2fd97b3c71f927d8583b386062ba8900e88e6855a4dd87aa0c4fea3bd", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "acd3d07a-cc70-491a-bad1-e6d517904c5a", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "55ee31809c9ce445c475409c7717b4e3e24b359ba9e5ff93321ab44cb4f5b509", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "92434103-0c11-4af3-b410-5bfd66be5608", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "6313f163e63998a43cf03df3e2e587c5fc8dc2c6b09971533fd1500359a8161e", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "decision on behalf of the organization and \nwho has or is perceived to have a financial, personal, or official interest in that decision of such \nnature that it may prevent him/her from acting in an impartial manner is obliged to excuse him/\nherself from the discussion and voting on said item. In the case of the Board, such instances are to \nbe recorded in the meeting minutes.  \nConflict of Interest Relating to Board Remuneration: The directors shall serve without remuneration, \nand no director shall directly or indirectly receive any profit from his position as such, provided that \na director may be paid reasonable expenses incurred by him in the performance of his duties. A \ndirector may, nonetheless, be paid for other service to the Charity, subject the prior approval of the \nBoard with that director abstaining.\nWhat the law says about Board members receiving payment:\nAccording to Articles 324 & 325 of the Quebec Provincial Civil Code, Board members are allowed \nto enter into contracts with the organization. However, such a situation must be made known \nto the Board; recorded in the meeting minutes; and", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 493, "end_char_idx": 1616, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "92434103-0c11-4af3-b410-5bfd66be5608": {"__data__": {"id_": "92434103-0c11-4af3-b410-5bfd66be5608", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include conflict of interest among board members, specifically in relation to financial interests and remuneration. It outlines the obligation for board members to excuse themselves from discussions and voting on matters where they have a personal interest, and the prohibition on directors receiving profit from their position. The section also mentions the possibility of directors being paid for other services to the organization, with approval from the Board and the director abstaining from the decision. The section references relevant articles of the Quebec Provincial Civil Code regarding board members entering into contracts with the organization.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the issue of conflicts of interest within nonprofit organizations, specifically related to Board members entering into contracts with the organization. It outlines the necessary steps for disclosing and addressing such situations, including recording in meeting minutes and obtaining Board approval. The section also mentions the legal considerations surrounding Board members receiving paid contracts, with a reference to Federal Common Law and the Quebec Provincial Civil Code. Additionally, it mentions the recommendation by Revenue Canada to include a conflict of interest statement in organizational by-laws for auditing purposes.", "section_summary": "The key topics of the section include the prohibition of directors from receiving profits from their position, the allowance for directors to be reimbursed for expenses incurred in the performance of their duties, and the conditions under which directors may be paid for other services to the charity. The section also discusses the legal requirements for board members entering into contracts with the organization, including disclosure, recording in meeting minutes, and approval by the board with the abstention of the board member in question. Additionally, the section outlines the differing perspectives of Quebec Provincial Civil Code and Federal Common Law regarding board members receiving paid contracts from nonprofit organizations, with a mention of Revenue Canada's auditing requirements.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does the Quebec Provincial Civil Code differ from Federal Common Law in terms of allowing Board members to enter into contracts with nonprofit organizations?\n2. What are the specific steps and requirements outlined for disclosing and addressing conflicts of interest related to Board members entering into contracts with the organization?\n3. How does Revenue Canada recommend nonprofit organizations address conflicts of interest within their by-laws for auditing purposes, specifically in relation to Board members receiving payment for services rendered to the charity?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "f087677d-dc40-4313-97b1-9556bc2a631b", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "53e0d4f2fd97b3c71f927d8583b386062ba8900e88e6855a4dd87aa0c4fea3bd", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "3c24b291-c5b7-4609-911b-a322b4689baa", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "fde996603157ace58e067a0d7eab173b64f28d4e861c63282bd80c06bdf3d7e1", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "18b163b5-3343-4e5a-b45a-a3f8d8dcf81d", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "aacf697ed19839ba4f484e7daebcb2aafe4db4209e3460b726a8baea6c48caa5", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "and no director shall directly or indirectly receive any profit from his position as such, provided that \na director may be paid reasonable expenses incurred by him in the performance of his duties. A \ndirector may, nonetheless, be paid for other service to the Charity, subject the prior approval of the \nBoard with that director abstaining.\nWhat the law says about Board members receiving payment:\nAccording to Articles 324 & 325 of the Quebec Provincial Civil Code, Board members are allowed \nto enter into contracts with the organization. However, such a situation must be made known \nto the Board; recorded in the meeting minutes; and approved by the Board, with the Board \nmember in question abstaining from the discussion and voting.\nAccording to Federal Common Law- Chapter 2 of the Corporate and Insolvency Law Policy,  the \nfederal court has always ruled against Board members receiving paid contracts from nonprofit \norganizations. However, the court also considers local context in its ruling and, in the case of \nQuebec, respects the Quebec Provincial Civil Code.\nAccording to Revenue Canada, the above sample by-law is sufficient for auditing", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 977, "end_char_idx": 2133, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "18b163b5-3343-4e5a-b45a-a3f8d8dcf81d": {"__data__": {"id_": "18b163b5-3343-4e5a-b45a-a3f8d8dcf81d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of the section include the prohibition of directors from receiving profits from their position, the allowance for directors to be reimbursed for expenses incurred in the performance of their duties, and the conditions under which directors may be paid for other services to the charity. The section also discusses the legal requirements for board members entering into contracts with the organization, including disclosure, recording in meeting minutes, and approval by the board with the abstention of the board member in question. Additionally, the section outlines the differing perspectives of Quebec Provincial Civil Code and Federal Common Law regarding board members receiving paid contracts from nonprofit organizations, with a mention of Revenue Canada's auditing requirements.", "next_section_summary": "The section provides a sample board self-assessment questionnaire for board members to evaluate their contributions to the organization. Key topics include attendance at meetings and events, preparation for meetings, active participation in discussions, familiarity with organizational documents, fulfilling board responsibilities, involvement in organization activities, knowledge of the organization, financial contributions, and overall satisfaction with board contributions. The entities mentioned in the section are board members, the organization, and the community.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the issue of conflicts of interest within nonprofit organizations, specifically related to Board members entering into contracts with the organization. It outlines the necessary steps for disclosing and addressing such situations, including recording in meeting minutes and obtaining Board approval. The section also mentions the legal considerations surrounding Board members receiving paid contracts, with a reference to Federal Common Law and the Quebec Provincial Civil Code. Additionally, it mentions the recommendation by Revenue Canada to include a conflict of interest statement in organizational by-laws for auditing purposes.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does Federal Common Law view Board members receiving paid contracts from nonprofit organizations, and how does this differ from the perspective of the Quebec Provincial Civil Code?\n2. What steps are recommended by Revenue Canada for nonprofit organizations to address conflicts of interest related to Board members entering into contracts with the organization?\n3. What specific legal requirements and procedures should be followed when a Board member enters into a contract with a nonprofit organization, as outlined in the section on conflicts of interest within nonprofit organizations?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "f087677d-dc40-4313-97b1-9556bc2a631b", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "53e0d4f2fd97b3c71f927d8583b386062ba8900e88e6855a4dd87aa0c4fea3bd", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "92434103-0c11-4af3-b410-5bfd66be5608", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "2fc8645854559b712a981a196d02454f8e5d51840707fc26cd7c4148902c7ee9", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "enter into contracts with the organization. However, such a situation must be made known \nto the Board; recorded in the meeting minutes; and approved by the Board, with the Board \nmember in question abstaining from the discussion and voting.\nAccording to Federal Common Law- Chapter 2 of the Corporate and Insolvency Law Policy,  the \nfederal court has always ruled against Board members receiving paid contracts from nonprofit \norganizations. However, the court also considers local context in its ruling and, in the case of \nQuebec, respects the Quebec Provincial Civil Code.\nAccording to Revenue Canada, the above sample by-law is sufficient for auditing purposes. However, \nthey did recommend that organizations add a \u201cconflict of interest statement\u201d to their by-laws. \n \nCONFLICT \nOF INTEREST\n\u2022\n\u2022\n\u2022", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1476, "end_char_idx": 2279, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "306b9430-6a7a-4785-85c7-b8cb4b1c193a": {"__data__": {"id_": "306b9430-6a7a-4785-85c7-b8cb4b1c193a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "20", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the issue of conflicts of interest within nonprofit organizations, specifically related to Board members entering into contracts with the organization. It outlines the necessary steps for disclosing and addressing such situations, including recording in meeting minutes and obtaining Board approval. The section also mentions the legal considerations surrounding Board members receiving paid contracts, with a reference to Federal Common Law and the Quebec Provincial Civil Code. Additionally, it mentions the recommendation by Revenue Canada to include a conflict of interest statement in organizational by-laws for auditing purposes.", "next_section_summary": "The section outlines the responsibilities and expectations of board members, including attending meetings, being familiar with the organization's charter and bylaws, actively participating in organization activities, making financial donations, acting in the best interest of the organization, and declaring conflicts of interest. Board members are also encouraged to fill out a survey to assess their performance and preparedness for their role.", "section_summary": "The section provides a sample board self-assessment questionnaire for board members to evaluate their contributions to the organization. Key topics include attendance at meetings and events, preparation for meetings, active participation in discussions, familiarity with organizational documents, fulfilling board responsibilities, involvement in organization activities, knowledge of the organization, financial contributions, and overall satisfaction with board contributions. The entities mentioned in the section are board members, the organization, and the community.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does the sample board self-assessment questionnaire in this document help board members evaluate their contributions to the organization and assess their preparedness for their role?\n2. What specific criteria are outlined in the sample board self-assessment questionnaire for board members to rate their performance, such as attendance at meetings, preparation for meetings, and financial contributions?\n3. How does the document address the issue of conflicts of interest within nonprofit organizations, particularly in relation to Board members entering into contracts with the organization, and what steps are outlined for disclosing and addressing such situations?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "9ce9c1e1-6fec-4e6d-903d-c766629c5150", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "20", "file_name": "COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\COCo-BoardOfDirectors-3-1.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 693818, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "31ea87a37e9ed3c81026d1928ce5bc7fb5651d71e0b207952df3127c468427f3", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "b66d1e82-082a-4611-91bf-871ca68c64ed", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "a2c6fadd63dd9abe35003892cc3df5dd1d0a03b5cadf35e12c4f5d59b366adf8", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "20\nSAMPLE BOARD SELF-ASSESMENT\nSAMPLE BOARD SELF-ASSESSMENT\n RATING 1 - 5             COMMENTS\nOverall, I am pleased with the contribution that I have \nmade to the organization as a Board member.\nI have attended the majority of board meetings and other \nevents requiring board participation. \nI prepare for meetings by reading background materials \nand researching issues for discussion.   \nI actively participate in Board meetings by listening, \ndiscussing & presenting complete information.  \n \nI am familiar with the organization\u2019s charter and bylaws. \n \nI carry out my other Board responsibilities (e.g., committee \nmember, officer duties) in an effective and timely manner.  \n \nI regula